<subSubSection lastPageId="91" lastPageNumber="92" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="90.[151,1437,1704,2017]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1740,1765]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Description</emphasis>
. 
<typeStatus box="[362,466,1740,1765]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Holotype</typeStatus>
(
<collectionCode box="[491,577,1741,1765]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">BMNH</collectionCode>
1923.1.13.1), complete, dark-yellow, body soft perhaps rotting when preserved, most neurochaetae broken (
<figureCitation box="[595,702,1776,1801]" captionStart="FIGURE 48" captionStartId="91.[151,250,1305,1327]" captionTargetBox="[175,1417,309,1283]" captionTargetId="figure@91.[170,1417,303,1283]" captionTargetPageId="91" captionText="FIGURE 48. Bradabyssa willeyi n. sp., holotype (BMNH 1923.1.13.1). A. Oblique dorsal view, posterior region twisted. B. Anterior end, dorsal view. C. Anterior end, ventral view (arrows point to gonopodial lobes). D. Mid-body chaetiger, right parapodium, posterior view (inset: close-up of neurochaetae). E. Posterior end, ventral view. Scale bars: A: 1.5 mm, B: 0.8 mm, C: 0.6 mm, D: 0.2 mm, E: 0.4 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041307/files/figure.png" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Fig. 48A</figureCitation>
); body 
<quantity box="[791,873,1777,1801]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.3" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" unit="mm" value="43.0">43 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[949,1017,1776,1801]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" unit="mm" value="6.0">6 mm</quantity>
wide, cephalic cage broken, chaetal length unknown, 55 chaetigers. Dorsal papillae arranged in 8–10 transverse rows, alternating in size (
<figureCitation box="[1318,1423,1812,1837]" captionStart="FIGURE 48" captionStartId="91.[151,250,1305,1327]" captionTargetBox="[175,1417,309,1283]" captionTargetId="figure@91.[170,1417,303,1283]" captionTargetPageId="91" captionText="FIGURE 48. Bradabyssa willeyi n. sp., holotype (BMNH 1923.1.13.1). A. Oblique dorsal view, posterior region twisted. B. Anterior end, dorsal view. C. Anterior end, ventral view (arrows point to gonopodial lobes). D. Mid-body chaetiger, right parapodium, posterior view (inset: close-up of neurochaetae). E. Posterior end, ventral view. Scale bars: A: 1.5 mm, B: 0.8 mm, C: 0.6 mm, D: 0.2 mm, E: 0.4 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041307/files/figure.png" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Fig. 48B</figureCitation>
). Each papilla long, with adhering fine sediment particles, forming rounded tubercles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="90.[151,1437,1704,2017]" box="[199,934,1884,1909]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Anterior end not observed, not dissected to avoid further damage.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="90.[151,1437,1704,2017]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Cephalic cage chaetae broken; size relationship to body length or width unknown. Chaetiger 1 apparently involved in cephalic cage; chaetal numbers unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="90.[151,1437,1704,2017]" box="[199,1437,1992,2017]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Anterior margin of first chaetiger papillated, papillae smaller than adjacent ones, probably in regeneration.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="91.[151,1436,151,248]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
Chaetigers 1–3 progressively longer. Chaetal transition from cephalic cage to body chaetae abrupt; bases of broken neurospines visible from chaetiger 2. Gonopodial lobes dark, blunt, apparently eroded, in chaetiger 5, and an additional one on left side of chaetiger 6 (
<figureCitation box="[618,721,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 48" captionStartId="91.[151,250,1305,1327]" captionTargetBox="[175,1417,309,1283]" captionTargetId="figure@91.[170,1417,303,1283]" captionTargetPageId="91" captionText="FIGURE 48. Bradabyssa willeyi n. sp., holotype (BMNH 1923.1.13.1). A. Oblique dorsal view, posterior region twisted. B. Anterior end, dorsal view. C. Anterior end, ventral view (arrows point to gonopodial lobes). D. Mid-body chaetiger, right parapodium, posterior view (inset: close-up of neurochaetae). E. Posterior end, ventral view. Scale bars: A: 1.5 mm, B: 0.8 mm, C: 0.6 mm, D: 0.2 mm, E: 0.4 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041307/files/figure.png" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Fig. 48C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041307/files/figure.png" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" targetBox="[175,1417,309,1283]" targetPageId="91">
<paragraph blockId="91.[151,1436,1305,1419]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,289,1305,1327]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">FIGURE 48.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2017" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" box="[296,492,1305,1327]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Bradabyssa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="willeyi" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[296,492,1305,1327]" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Bradabyssa willeyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[499,563,1305,1326]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[499,558,1305,1326]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
,
</emphasis>
holotype (BMNH 1923.1.13.1). A. Oblique dorsal view, posterior region twisted. B. Anterior end, dorsal view. C. Anterior end, ventral view (arrows point to gonopodial lobes). D. Mid-body chaetiger, right parapodium, posterior view (inset: close-up of neurochaetae). E. Posterior end, ventral view. Scale bars: A: 1.5 mm, B: 0.8 mm, C: 0.6 mm, D: 0.2 mm, E: 0.4 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="91.[151,1437,1458,2034]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
Parapodia lateral, neuropodia ventrolateral. Parapodial lobes barely developed, chaetae appearing as emerging from body wall (
<figureCitation box="[351,460,1497,1522]" captionStart="FIGURE 48" captionStartId="91.[151,250,1305,1327]" captionTargetBox="[175,1417,309,1283]" captionTargetId="figure@91.[170,1417,303,1283]" captionTargetPageId="91" captionText="FIGURE 48. Bradabyssa willeyi n. sp., holotype (BMNH 1923.1.13.1). A. Oblique dorsal view, posterior region twisted. B. Anterior end, dorsal view. C. Anterior end, ventral view (arrows point to gonopodial lobes). D. Mid-body chaetiger, right parapodium, posterior view (inset: close-up of neurochaetae). E. Posterior end, ventral view. Scale bars: A: 1.5 mm, B: 0.8 mm, C: 0.6 mm, D: 0.2 mm, E: 0.4 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041307/files/figure.png" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Fig. 48D</figureCitation>
). Notopodial lobe low, with 1–2 inferior papillae, as long as 1/8 notochaetal length; neuropodial lobe slightly more developed, with 2 superior, and 2–3 inferior papillae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="91.[151,1437,1458,2034]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
Median notochaetae arranged in transverse row; all notochaetae multiarticulate capillaries, articles short basally, medium-sized medially and subdistally, long distally, 5–6 per bundle, as long as about 1/3 body width. Neurochaetae tapered spines, mostly broken, with very short rings throughout pigmented region, subdistally hyaline, probably aristate (
<figureCitation box="[450,553,1685,1710]" captionStart="FIGURE 32" captionStartId="64.[151,250,1425,1447]" captionTargetBox="[175,1416,642,1385]" captionTargetId="figure@64.[171,1418,638,1389]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURE 32. Bradabyssa harrisae n. sp. A. Holotype (LACM 9552), right lateral view. B. Paratype (LACM 9553), anterior end, dorsal view. C. Holotype, anterior end, ventral view (arrows point to gonopodial lobes). D. Same, enlarged (arrows point to gonopodial lobes). E. Chaetiger 11, right parapodium, posterior view (inset: neurochaetal tips). Scale bars. A: 1.2 mm, B: 0. 3 mm, C: 0.7 mm, D: 0.2 mm, E: 230 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041274/files/figure.png" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Fig. 32D</figureCitation>
, inset).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="91.[151,1437,1458,2034]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
Posterior region tapered into a blunt cone, terminal segments without papillae, probably eroded (
<figureCitation box="[1319,1423,1721,1746]" captionStart="FIGURE 32" captionStartId="64.[151,250,1425,1447]" captionTargetBox="[175,1416,642,1385]" captionTargetId="figure@64.[171,1418,638,1389]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURE 32. Bradabyssa harrisae n. sp. A. Holotype (LACM 9552), right lateral view. B. Paratype (LACM 9553), anterior end, dorsal view. C. Holotype, anterior end, ventral view (arrows point to gonopodial lobes). D. Same, enlarged (arrows point to gonopodial lobes). E. Chaetiger 11, right parapodium, posterior view (inset: neurochaetal tips). Scale bars. A: 1.2 mm, B: 0. 3 mm, C: 0.7 mm, D: 0.2 mm, E: 230 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041274/files/figure.png" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Fig. 32E</figureCitation>
); pygidium depressed, anus flat, ventroterminal, muscular ring, without anal cirri.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="92" lastPageNumber="93" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="91.[151,1437,1458,2034]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1793,1818]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Remarks</emphasis>
. As indicated in the key above, 
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2017" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" box="[685,902,1793,1818]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Bradabyssa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="willeyi" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[685,902,1793,1818]" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Bradabyssa willeyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[911,977,1793,1818]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[911,969,1793,1818]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">n. sp</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2017" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" box="[1108,1262,1793,1818]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Bradabyssa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="hartmanae" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1108,1262,1793,1818]" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">B. hartmanae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1272,1337,1793,1818]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1272,1337,1793,1818]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
because both have notochaetae with basal articles short to medium-sized, and 9–10 transverse rows of dorsal papillae. They differ, however, in the relative density of dorsal papillae and in the pigmentation of gonopodial lobes; in 
<emphasis box="[1412,1429,1866,1889]" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">B</emphasis>
. “ 
<emphasis box="[163,273,1902,1925]" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">gangetica</emphasis>
” papillae are distinct individually and gonopodial lobes are darker, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" box="[1184,1338,1901,1926]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Bradabyssa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="hartmanae">
<emphasis box="[1184,1338,1901,1926]" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">B. hartmanae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
papillae are laterally fused such that the body wall is not visible, and gonopodial lobes are a similarl colour to the adjacent body wall.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="91.[151,1437,1458,2034]" lastBlockId="92.[151,1437,151,464]" lastPageId="92" lastPageNumber="93" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
This species is described despite the poor condition of the single specimen, and the lack of complete neurochaetae, which do not allow a complete description. During the R.I.M.S. Investigator expedition (Anonymous 1914), there were two stations labelled off the Ganges Delta, indicating some specimens were found in 
<quantity box="[180,310,223,248]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9899999999999998" metricValueMax="4.05" metricValueMin="1.93" pageId="92" pageNumber="93" unit="m" value="299.0" valueMax="405.0" valueMin="193.0">
193– 
<specimenCount box="[234,310,223,248]" pageId="92" pageNumber="93" type="generic">405 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
. More specimens in good condition are needed to describe it more fully.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="92" pageNumber="93" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="92.[151,1437,151,464]" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,260,285]" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">Etymology</emphasis>
: This species is named after Dr. Arthur Willey. He was Director of the Colombo Museum, 
<collectingCountry name="Sri Lanka" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">
<collectingRegion box="[1403,1436,260,285]" country="United Kingdom" name="Surrey" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">Sri</collectingRegion>
Lanka
</collectingCountry>
, editor of their journal Spolia Zeylanica, and paid some attention to local fisheries. During this residence, he made some publications dealing with polychaetes and separated the 
<typeStatus box="[920,1018,332,357]" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">holotype</typeStatus>
for this species, but did not finish its description.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="92" pageNumber="93" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="92.[151,1437,151,464]" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,404,429]" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">Distribution</emphasis>
. Only known from a single specimen, probably collected off the Ganges delta after the initial naming as gangetica.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
